'''David Weyhe Smith''' (September 24, 1926 – January 23 1981) was an American [[pediatrician]] and [[Dysmorphology|dysmorphologist]].
 
Smith was born in [[Oakland]], [[California]]. He gained his medical degree from [[Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine]] and worked with [[Lawson Wilkins]] in the field of [[pediatric endocrinology]].<ref>[http://www.springerlink.com/content/m81642275780p0gx/ ''American Journal of Pediatrics'' Obituary]</ref> He began working at the [[University of Wisconsin School of Medicine and Public Health]] in 1958, and became a professor of pediatrics there. From 1966 until the end of his career he was at the [[University of Washington]], Seattle. His work in dysmorphology was recognized worldwide.

His book ''Recognizable Patterns of Human Malformation'' is considered a key work in the field.  He also published five other monographs as well as nearly 200 papers.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Smith |first=David W. |year=1970 |title=Recognizable Patterns of Human Malformation: Genetic, Embryologic, and Clinical Aspects |journal=Major Problems in Clinical Pediatrics |volume=7 |pages=368 |quote=|pmc= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=McKusick |first=Victor A. |year=1973 |month=May |title=Recognizable patterns of human malformation: Genetic, embryologic, and clinical aspects |journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=327 |quote= |pmc=1706730}}</ref> The condition known as [[Aase Smith syndrome]] is named for Smith and colleague [[Jon Morton Aase]]. Smith also co-discovered and lent his name to such conditions as [[Smith-Lemli-Opitz syndrome]], [[Marshall-Smith syndrome]] and others.

[[Fetal Alcohol Syndrome]] was named in 1973 by Smith and Dr. Kenneth Lyons Jones, who identified a pattern of "craniofacial, limb, and cardiovascular defects associated with prenatal onset growth deficiency and developmental delay" in eight unrelated children of three [[Ethnicity|ethnic]] groups, all born to mothers who were [[alcoholic]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Jones K.L., Smith D.W. | year = 1973 | title = Recognition of the fetal alcohol syndrome in early infancy | url = | journal = Lancet | volume = 2 | issue = 7836| pages = 999–1001 | pmid = 4127281 }}</ref>

Smith died of cancer in [[Seattle, Washington]].

